{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "In summary, mechanization, electrification, and automation propelled the first three revolutions, progressively converting the manual agricultural economy into one centered on manufacturing.",
    "These revolutions improved the standard of living for industry workers and the rest of the world, benefitting from production outcomes and potential [21,22].The fourth industrial revolution, Industry 4.0 (I4.0), was introduced around 2011 at the Hannover Fair in Germany.",
    "It refers to the digitization of the manufacturing sector where state-of-the-art technologies, methods, and approaches such as artificial intelligence (AI), Internet of Things (IoT), machine learning (ML), Cyber-Physical systems (CPS), Digital twins, cloud computing, and additive manufacturing are exploited and integrated into factories production processes to achieve a more flexible, agile, and highly efficient manufacturing environment [26].",
    "The I4.0 paradigm aims to improve the automation concept introduced by the previous industrial revolution (Industry 3.0) while ensuring better interconnectivity between manufacturing stakeholders and optimizing real-time operations [27,28].",
    "Thanks to advanced technologies integrated into their production processes with the I4.0 concept, factories can improve their decision-making processes in real time, driven by the amount of data insight shared between connected devices and entities [29]."
  ],
